⸻

9. Conclusion

This paper has argued that language is not a system, not a structure, and not a stable object of study. It is instead a continuously mutating byproduct of human interaction that resists capture precisely because it is alive.

Accordingly, the Infinite Accent Branching Initiative formally concludes that:
	•	Accents cannot be mapped
	•	Meanings cannot be fixed
	•	Context cannot be abstracted
	•	And any model claiming otherwise has already failed, albeit confidently

Further research is therefore unnecessary, ongoing, and urgently funded.

⸻

End of Document



⸻

Addendum IV: Temporal Validity and the Mandatory Reading Window

9.1 The Ephemerality Clause

The author is advised—indeed institutionally obligated—to include a Temporal Validity Warning stating that this paper possesses a Maximum Semantic Half-Life (MSHL) of approximately six (6) weeks from first reading, printing, forwarding, or aggressive nodding in agreement.

After this period, the document’s lexical payload will have undergone sufficient semantic drift, irony saturation, and contextual re-interpretation as to render any subsequent reading:
	•	Conceptually inaccurate
	•	Socially misaligned
	•	Retroactively embarrassing
	•	Or accidentally political

Accordingly, readers encountering this paper beyond the prescribed window are no longer engaging with this document, but with a descendant artefact bearing only superficial resemblance to the original.

⸻

9.2 Drift Liability Waiver

By continuing to read beyond the six-week threshold, the reader implicitly agrees that:
	•	Key terms may no longer mean what they meant when written
	•	Examples may have inverted polarity (serious → ironic → sincere again)
	•	The author’s intent may have escaped into adjacent discourse communities
	•	Footnotes may now function as jokes, warnings, or slurs depending on platform

The institution accepts no responsibility for misunderstandings arising from delayed comprehension.

⸻

9.3 Preemptive Obsolescence Declaration

This paper therefore declares itself obsolete in advance, not due to error, but due to accuracy.

Its arguments are correct only in the narrow temporal corridor in which they are read, discussed, and misquoted. Preservation efforts, archiving, or citation in future contexts should be regarded as archaeological activities, not scholarly ones.

⸻

9.4 Final Instruction to the Reader

If you are reading this document within six weeks of its circulation, proceed urgently.

If you are reading it after that period, you may as well not read it at all—
because whatever you think it says now
is already something else.

⸻

This addendum contradicts the rest of the paper by confirming it was never stable enough to need clarification.
